  abstract  = {Proof-theoretic semantics is an alternative to truth-conditionsemantics. It is based on the fundamental assumption that the centralnotion in terms of which meanings are assigned to certain expressionsof our language, in particular to logical constants, is that ofproof rather than truth. In this senseproof-theoretic semantics is semantics in terms of proof.Proof-theoretic semantics also means the semantics of proofs,i.e., the semantics of entities which describe how we arrive atcertain assertions given certain assumptions. Both aspects ofproof-theoretic semantics can be intertwined, i.e. the semantics ofproofs is itself often given in terms of proofs.},
